menu "esptag configuration"

choice ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_CHOICE
    prompt "Log level for esptag's own modules"
    default ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_INFO
    help
        Runtime log level applied at startup to this project's own log tags
        (main, crypto, nvs_store, tag, ble_adv). The system-wide default stays
        at WARN (see CONFIG_LOG_DEFAULT_LEVEL), keeping the IDF / NimBLE /
        controller components quiet; this only adjusts our own modules.

        Levels above WARN require CONFIG_LOG_MAXIMUM_LEVEL to be high enough
        for the calls to be compiled in (this project compiles VERBOSE in).

    config ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_NONE
        bool "No output"
    config ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_ERROR
        bool "Error"
    config ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_WARN
        bool "Warning"
    config ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_INFO
        bool "Info"
    config ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_DEBUG
        bool "Debug"
    config ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_VERBOSE
        bool "Verbose"
endchoice

config ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL
    int
    # Values match the esp_log_level_t enum (NONE=0 .. VERBOSE=5).
    default 0 if ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_NONE
    default 1 if ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_ERROR
    default 2 if ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_WARN
    default 3 if ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_INFO
    default 4 if ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_DEBUG
    default 5 if ESPTAG_OWN_LOG_LEVEL_VERBOSE

config ESPTAG_ROTATE_ENABLE
    bool "Rotate the advertising key/identifier"
    default y
    help
        Periodically advance an epoch: ratchet the symmetric key, derive a fresh
        advertising identifier, and re-advertise under it (every
        CONFIG_ESPTAG_ROTATE_INTERVAL_MS). This is the privacy core of the
        design — rotating identities is what stops a passive observer from
        linking sightings over time.

        Disable only for debugging or characterisation where you want the tag to
        keep advertising under a single, static identity: the rotation timer is
        never armed, so it stays at the boot epoch indefinitely.

config ESPTAG_ROTATE_INTERVAL_MS
    int "Key/identifier rotation interval (ms)"
    default 900000
    range 1000 86400000
    help
        How often the tag advances an epoch: ratchets the symmetric key, derives
        a fresh advertising identifier, and re-advertises under it. The default
        of 900000 ms (15 min) matches the Find My cadence; lower it to a few
        seconds to watch rotation happen while testing.

config ESPTAG_ADV_INTERVAL_MS
    int "BLE advertising interval (ms)"
    default 2000
    range 20 10240
    help
        How often a BLE legacy advertising event fires. One advertising event
        sweeps all three primary channels (37/38/39) exactly once, so this is
        effectively "one broadcast per channel per window". itvl_min and
        itvl_max are both pinned to this value (see ble_adv.c), giving a fixed
        interval with no min/max jitter; the controller still adds the
        spec-mandated 0-10 ms advDelay on top.

        The range matches the BLE legacy non-connectable advertising limits
        (20 ms .. 10240 ms).

config ESPTAG_PERSIST_COUNTER
    bool "Persist rotation counter across reboots"
    default y
    help
        Persist the rotation counter to a writable NVS namespace and, at boot,
        fast-forward the symmetric-key ratchet to that epoch (crypto_advance_sk).
        This stops the tag from replaying the same identifier sequence
        (p_0, p_1, ...) after every power cycle — a linkability regression for a
        privacy design.

        When set, the counter is read at startup and written after each epoch
        advance. When unset, the tag always boots at counter 0 and never writes
        the counter — an ephemeral mode for testing (rapid rotation with no flash
        wear and reproducible from-zero behavior).

config ESPTAG_ZEROIZE
    bool "Scrub intermediate key material (zeroize)"
    default y
    help
        Scrub all intermediate key material (scalars, SK ratchet state) with
        mbedtls_platform_zeroize on every path, including error paths. When set,
        CONFIG_ESPTAG_ZEROIZE gates those #ifdef guards in the sources directly.

        Leave enabled for any real build; only disable for local debugging where
        you want to inspect that material left on the stack.

endmenu
